01:48.658 --> 01:50.257
My name is Johannes,

01:50.365 --> 01:52.086
and I have a condition.

01:52.729 --> 01:53.966
I'm human.

01:54.132 --> 01:57.925
I first realized that when
I fell on my face on a concrete slab

01:58.212 --> 02:00.002
on a beach in Italy.

02:00.889 --> 02:02.160
I was four.

02:02.429 --> 02:04.262
And it was clear to me:

02:04.559 --> 02:06.927
beaches cannot be trusted,

02:07.179 --> 02:08.872
I hated Italy,

02:09.048 --> 02:11.502
and dreams can be broken.

02:12.297 --> 02:14.738
The human is a narrative being.

02:14.992 --> 02:16.843
We construct emotional machines...

02:16.912 --> 02:19.305
so called stories, to communicate

02:19.366 --> 02:21.425
to share the world in which we live

02:21.428 --> 02:23.770
and make it collectively experienceable.

02:24.158 --> 02:26.385
And we're pretty good
at doing that.

02:26.553 --> 02:31.145
Since the primoridial zoo
Mendelized into primate brains,

02:31.153 --> 02:33.580
we have either been fleeing
from big cats

02:33.582 --> 02:36.026
or telling others about
our escapes

02:36.030 --> 02:38.921
from the clutches of big cats.

02:39.520 --> 02:41.113
Sitting around a campfire

02:41.140 --> 02:43.582
interpreting and
breaking-down the world,

02:43.643 --> 02:45.243
charging it with meaning,

02:45.481 --> 02:49.777
regardless of whether the details hold up
to a <i>Wikipedia</i> check, or not.

02:50.222 --> 02:52.542
The human is also a political being,

02:52.667 --> 02:56.127
although many members of my species
don't like that idea.

02:56.806 --> 02:58.106
Get used to it.

02:58.192 --> 03:00.233
You can't avoid being politcal.

03:00.338 --> 03:04.583
The moment you choose to buy
a sugar-free <i>Red Bull™</i> at <i>Walmart™,</i>

03:04.618 --> 03:06.683
you commit a political act.

03:06.801 --> 03:09.053
The same is true when you
drag a royalty-free

03:09.055 --> 03:11.816
hip-hop version
of Pachelbel's <i>Canon in D</i>

03:11.905 --> 03:13.305
into your shopping basket @

03:13.307 --> 03:15.252
—►    pond5.com    ◄—

03:15.371 --> 03:19.325
{\an8}Politics is the practice of
distribution of power and resources

03:19.352 --> 03:24.263
within the given community as well as
the interrelationship between communities.

03:24.638 --> 03:25.638
Period.

03:25.860 --> 03:28.930
We project a certain story
out to the world.

03:29.210 --> 03:33.357
The story differs if you are a leftist,
a progressive, or conservative,

03:33.423 --> 03:34.552
but be assured,

03:34.634 --> 03:37.429
most people I know
who call themselves anarchists

03:37.431 --> 03:39.614
are just stupid libertarians.

03:40.280 --> 03:45.015
We communicate our views by
using narrative and conceptual shortcuts.

03:45.236 --> 03:46.753
Abbreviated terms like:

03:46.778 --> 03:50.122
"freedom" or "privacy"
and so on.

03:50.391 --> 03:52.646
These shortcuts are important.

03:52.814 --> 03:56.030
{\an8}If someone had called
'global warming' something different,

03:56.033 --> 03:58.826
{\an8}let's say, 'atmosphere cancer,'

03:59.190 --> 04:02.074
you wouldn't have problems
explaining why it's a bad thing.

04:02.789 --> 04:07.671
I always wanted to create a glossary
of all-important terms.

04:07.906 --> 04:10.749
Because Jesus Fuckin' McChrist,

04:10.787 --> 04:15.860
they're always used and abused
in common sections on the World Wide Web.

04:16.370 --> 04:21.564
I wanted to give some of these
golden calfs of discourse a second look,

04:21.781 --> 04:26.650
to explain, re-evaluate,
and maybe even sacrifice them.

04:26.970 --> 04:29.544
I teamed up with my
good friend Ishan Raval,

04:29.749 --> 04:32.790
{\an8}who definitely matches me
in my political leanings.

04:32.992 --> 04:36.686
{\an8}I mean, look,
we both have our hands on our chins

04:36.931 --> 04:38.494
in our <i>Google</i> profile pics.

04:39.616 --> 04:41.099
Pompous little fucks we are.

04:41.256 --> 04:44.047
And because I know
a lot of creative performers

04:44.239 --> 04:47.081
who will do pretty much anything
for almost nothing,

04:47.124 --> 04:48.758
I decided to make this film.

04:48.817 --> 04:51.321
<i>How much longer
do I have to hold this shit?    It's heavy!</i>

04:51.389 --> 04:55.014
Well, y-you can put it in your resumé.
I mean come on... a little bit longer.

04:55.708 --> 04:57.772
<i>-And we used my car.</i>

04:58.067 --> 05:00.755
You're the head of
transportation fleets, okay?

05:01.015 --> 05:02.612
So, well, never forget,

05:02.828 --> 05:04.296
you don't hate Italy,

05:04.520 --> 05:05.991
you hate capitalism.

05:06.153 --> 05:09.784
What a big word!
So big!

05:10.104 --> 05:11.760
Capitalism.

05:12.280 --> 05:15.343
One of the biggest words I know...
and I know a lot of words.

05:15.634 --> 05:16.634
There's

05:16.659 --> 05:21.428
"Market"  (true, but that one
sounds a bit too mystical).

05:22.531 --> 05:25.556
Oh!
I think that's Brian Ewok.

05:25.801 --> 05:27.378
Good to have a
comfy seat

05:27.385 --> 05:29.902
at my favorite hippster
coffee shop and wine bar

05:29.959 --> 05:31.425
enjoying free Wi-Fi

05:31.656 --> 05:34.564
from a network
whose password is  "Helvetica."

05:34.718 --> 05:36.446
I'm just
minding my own business,

05:36.472 --> 05:38.889
when I get spotted
by Madame Juju,

05:38.971 --> 05:41.615
the friendly hippster
coffee shop and wine bar owner

05:41.713 --> 05:43.391
who does sweat yoga.

05:43.450 --> 05:45.922
<i>Hello.
How can I help you?</i>

05:45.959 --> 05:49.893
<i>A double eggnog frappucino
with tofu-breaded halibut?</i>

05:50.080 --> 05:53.280
There's a sticker for the
Green Party candidate behind the bar.

05:53.382 --> 05:56.403
<i>Oh, I  </i> love  <i>the Greens!</i>

05:56.488 --> 05:59.202
<i>So friendly!  So caring!</i>

05:59.329 --> 06:00.976
<i>So cuddly!</i>

06:01.186 --> 06:02.901
Marx once called the State

06:02.903 --> 06:06.979
a committee for managing the
common affairs of the whole bourgeoisie.

06:07.373 --> 06:09.687
Thank the non-existing God for it!

06:09.749 --> 06:14.152
Because where management is possible,
so also is mismanagement.

06:14.388 --> 06:16.588
And some parts of the bourgeoisie,

06:16.753 --> 06:20.897
especially those who do sweat yoga
and keep their hearts wholesome,

06:21.029 --> 06:25.075
might be persuaded to use
that committee against their interests.

06:25.452 --> 06:29.304
Basically, there are people
who own the means of production.

06:29.379 --> 06:34.662
Let's say fancy coffee machines,
or servers, or farms, or server farms.

06:34.819 --> 06:36.587
That's the bourgeoisie.

06:36.829 --> 06:41.162
And then there are people who don't own
the means of production or capital,

06:41.365 --> 06:43.420
so they have to sell their work.

06:43.572 --> 06:47.702
The workers.   That's all the barristas
and sandwich artists

06:47.705 --> 06:49.754
and <i>Ryanair®</i> check in personnel.

06:49.819 --> 06:54.290
But even if the bourgeoisie,
which includes Madame Juju,

06:54.423 --> 06:57.724
might not be united
in its political allegiances

06:58.015 --> 06:59.744
they play the same purpose.

06:59.803 --> 07:01.256
It isn't her fault.

07:01.310 --> 07:03.146
<i>It isn't my fault.</i>

07:03.341 --> 07:06.075
In all corners and cortices of her brain,

07:06.195 --> 07:08.422
she might just regard this as her job.

07:08.590 --> 07:10.136
 An innocent livelihood.

07:10.160 --> 07:12.431
And even,
a community service.

07:12.664 --> 07:16.144
<i>Oh, absolutely!
People love me.</i>

07:16.345 --> 07:21.291
<i>I am the Maggie Gyllenhaal
of safron-based cake frosting.</i>

07:21.492 --> 07:23.305
All of that, it might be.

07:23.603 --> 07:27.605
But capitalism is bigger than
any of our lives and wills.

07:27.803 --> 07:31.662
It produces net effects
some capitalists don't realize.

07:31.904 --> 07:35.106
Madame Juju's heart may not
be driven by profit,

07:35.365 --> 07:37.200
but her business must be.

07:37.333 --> 07:39.511
Money must make more money.

07:39.708 --> 07:41.241
More money must be made

07:41.558 --> 07:45.534
so that it can keep up with competing
coffee shops and wine bars,

07:45.632 --> 07:49.929
which are constatly coming up
and trying to out-perform Madame Juju.

07:50.075 --> 07:52.182
<i>It makes me cry.</i>

07:52.372 --> 07:56.500
<i>It's not even enough for me
to earn back the money I invested.</i>

07:57.004 --> 08:00.823
<i>There has to be a good return
on investment.</i>

08:02.526 --> 08:05.708
<i>There have to be upgrades
to match the latest</i>

08:05.759 --> 08:08.307
<i>speedy, spicy, sprinkle trends;</i>

08:08.404 --> 08:11.184
<i>or to keep paying an increasing rent</i>

08:11.219 --> 08:14.148
<i>so that the coffee
doesn't get more expensive.</i>

08:14.213 --> 08:17.199
<i>Otherwise, everyone will go to...</i>

08:17.576 --> 08:20.471
<i>Monsieur Dudu's down the street.</i>

08:20.543 --> 08:21.543
It's true.

08:21.545 --> 08:23.022
His coffee is okay,

08:23.174 --> 08:26.473
but his wine selection
is out of this world.

08:26.711 --> 08:29.606
So, Madame Juju
is forced to cut costs

08:29.712 --> 08:31.654
by not protecting the environment,

08:31.824 --> 08:34.006
or by paying super-low wages.

08:34.097 --> 08:36.080
<i>It is so very sad</i>

08:36.270 --> 08:38.938
<i>but, I donate to</i>
Amnesty International.

08:39.297 --> 08:43.557
Overall, the wealth of the world
increases on the side of the capital,

08:43.602 --> 08:46.237
be it money uninvested and stagnant...

08:46.315 --> 08:49.890
<i>There are some trillions of dollars
around like that today.</i>

08:49.947 --> 08:52.831
or the things required
for and by business.

08:52.983 --> 08:55.562
And wealth decreases
on the side of the world

08:55.590 --> 08:57.125
where costs are cut.

08:57.254 --> 08:59.995
People working for wages
and the world itself.

09:00.375 --> 09:02.397
Take atmosphere cancer.

09:02.505 --> 09:05.300
Sadly it's not capitalism's
side-effect,

09:05.502 --> 09:07.916
but a sign of its normal functioning.

09:08.006 --> 09:10.901
The system was for the last
one hundred years,

09:11.039 --> 09:14.461
running on cheap oil
and making a huge profit with it.

09:14.715 --> 09:17.306
Money still needs
to make more money.

09:17.411 --> 09:21.137
So more and more things
have to be exchangeable for money.

09:21.485 --> 09:24.931
Everything from gummy bears
to DNA sequences,

09:25.138 --> 09:27.169
to carbon dioxide emissions.

09:27.337 --> 09:29.309
<i>But Friedman says that</i>

09:29.344 --> 09:34.113
<i>economic freedom is the
precondition for political freedom.</i>

09:34.217 --> 09:35.587
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

09:35.644 --> 09:37.729
Not so fast, Madame Juju.

09:37.897 --> 09:41.623
Well, freedom is a huge word too,
yes, yes, but

09:41.767 --> 09:43.520
in the capitalist society

09:43.602 --> 09:45.442
there is only one freedom:

09:45.603 --> 09:47.797
the freedom of the market.

09:48.387 --> 09:52.945
At its root, capitalism is based on
three simple things:

09:53.352 --> 09:54.837
working for a wage,

09:54.954 --> 09:58.729
private ownership, or control of
the means of production,

09:58.984 --> 10:02.501
and production
for exchange and profit.

10:02.717 --> 10:06.204
And, it's all sold
with the promise of liberty.

10:06.414 --> 10:09.587
<i>But that has been true
since the beginning of time.</i>

10:09.648 --> 10:12.923
Capitalism didn't arise
according to natural laws

10:12.966 --> 10:14.989
that stem from human nature.

10:15.117 --> 10:17.852
It was spread by organized violence.

10:18.075 --> 10:20.002
The concept of private land

10:20.061 --> 10:24.344
and means of production might seem like
the natural state of things now,

10:24.439 --> 10:28.354
however, we should remember
it is a human concept... .

10:28.486 --> 10:30.420
First in places like England:

10:30.625 --> 10:34.822
enclosures drove self-sufficient peasants
from communal land

10:34.904 --> 10:37.592
into the cities to work in factories.

10:37.666 --> 10:40.243
Under the reign of
Henry the Eighth alone,

10:40.521 --> 10:43.516
72,000 people were executed

10:43.679 --> 10:45.238
for vagabondage.

10:45.298 --> 10:46.529
Is that freedom?

10:46.634 --> 10:51.891
Later, capitalism was spread rapidly
and violently around the globe.

10:52.207 --> 10:55.079
Do you remember
that nice little girl,  Alice?

10:55.383 --> 10:57.002
<i>Oh, yes, certainly!</i>

10:57.303 --> 10:58.403
<i>Lovely!</i>

10:58.786 --> 11:02.202
She fell into Wonderland,
used its resources,

11:02.394 --> 11:05.015
and was highly judgmental of the natives.

11:05.195 --> 11:08.202
A spoiled British imperialist brat!

11:08.525 --> 11:10.153
But the Germans weren't
much better.

11:10.260 --> 11:12.176
It's the year 1818.

11:12.703 --> 11:15.294
Powerful German merchants
started to profit

11:15.594 --> 11:18.932
from overseas commerce
in Asia and Africa.

11:19.215 --> 11:24.327
The German Empire supported this expansion
by conquering large amounts of land

11:24.453 --> 11:27.253
and established so-called "protectorates."

11:27.408 --> 11:30.369
With fraud, Bible, alcohol and violence,

11:30.504 --> 11:35.490
the German Empire grew to a staggering
2.6 million square kilometers,

11:35.783 --> 11:38.601
five times the size of Germany...

11:38.947 --> 11:41.381
reaching the third place
in colonial power,

11:41.628 --> 11:43.694
right after England and France.

11:44.459 --> 11:47.926
The following sarcastic folk song,
written in 1819,

11:48.360 --> 11:50.870
has its own perspective on the matter:

12:45.217 --> 12:46.455
<i>But wait!</i>

12:46.635 --> 12:48.475
<i>I like black people.</i>

12:48.863 --> 12:50.703
<i>They've got the rhythm.</i>

12:50.877 --> 12:54.002
<i>Equality and justice for everyone.</i>

12:54.418 --> 12:56.575
<i>I don't like the super rich.</i>

12:56.720 --> 12:59.489
<i>The middle class is under attack.</i>

12:59.939 --> 13:03.016
<i>The goddamn politicians are to blame.</i>

13:03.258 --> 13:05.310
Most liberal cosmopolitan folks

13:05.335 --> 13:09.687
lack faith in public institutions,
ideals and poliiticians.

13:09.976 --> 13:12.276
The notoriety of left-leaning authors

13:12.278 --> 13:15.746
like Michael Moore
or, (gasps) Noam Chomsky,

13:15.902 --> 13:18.952
shows that our fellow humans
know very well

13:19.041 --> 13:21.582
what Moore claims is the awful truth,

13:21.782 --> 13:24.112
but they act as if they don't know.

13:24.446 --> 13:27.718
We have to realize that
everyone is part of the problem.

13:28.005 --> 13:31.677
It's our habits, our procedures,
that keep the game going.

13:31.989 --> 13:34.144
There is no good or bad capitalism.

13:34.226 --> 13:37.701
Inequality is an integral
part of capitalism.

13:37.792 --> 13:42.085
Everything including humans,
is treated as a mere resource.

13:42.248 --> 13:44.206
<i>I like punk rock.</i>

13:44.296 --> 13:46.435
<i>I make my own sweaters.</i>

13:46.544 --> 13:48.821
<i>I recycle plastic bottles.</i>

13:48.935 --> 13:52.105
<i>I enjoy books by Terry Pratchett.</i>

13:52.187 --> 13:54.090
<i>I am a Buddhist.</i>

13:54.493 --> 13:55.826
That is nice of you.

13:55.981 --> 13:58.674
But remember that
market driven capitalism

13:58.780 --> 14:01.454
musters the quasi-scientific discourses

14:01.458 --> 14:03.858
of marketing and public relations

14:03.941 --> 14:06.769
and increasingly, eastern religion,

14:06.799 --> 14:09.066
to recommend products to consumers

14:09.241 --> 14:12.900
as necessary means
in the liberal pursuit of happiness,

14:13.045 --> 14:16.432
self-fulfillment and personal freedom.

14:16.588 --> 14:21.669
{\an8}Sometimes, there is
so much beauty in the world!

14:21.986 --> 14:25.324
{\an8}I feel like I can't take it!

14:25.476 --> 14:29.250
<i>Well, capitalism has its downsides.</i>

14:29.441 --> 14:33.572
<i>But, it's way better than communism...
...that's really bad!</i>

14:33.574 --> 14:35.392
<i>It killed people!</i>

14:35.563 --> 14:38.919
<i>Even worse... it didn't work.</i>

14:39.144 --> 14:41.313
Let us quote Marx himself:

14:41.562 --> 14:43.401
"The categorical imperative

14:43.887 --> 14:45.887
"is to overthrow all relations

14:45.961 --> 14:47.279
"in which man

14:47.369 --> 14:52.066
is a debased, enslaved, forsaken,
despicable being."

14:52.531 --> 14:55.317
This imperative is true for all conditions.

14:55.481 --> 15:00.540
Even the ones created by perverted
misinterpretaions of his writings.

15:00.709 --> 15:03.234
State communism killed a ton of people

15:03.377 --> 15:04.816
and the sad truth

15:04.849 --> 15:07.839
is that it was based
on the principle of a state.

15:07.901 --> 15:10.034
It created forms of property.

15:10.215 --> 15:13.498
It had banks, police, even a market.

15:13.749 --> 15:16.752
State communism was a badly adapted,

15:16.810 --> 15:19.733
botched version
of the rules of capitalism.

15:19.817 --> 15:21.880
We shouldn't shed a tear for it.

15:22.114 --> 15:26.324
<i>True, and socialism
penalizes high achievers,</i>

15:26.434 --> 15:31.119
<i>rewards laziness, cuts freedom
and stifles choice.</i>

15:31.258 --> 15:32.638
<i>Ayn Rand says,</i>

15:32.744 --> 15:34.750
Ayn Rand died on welfare.

15:35.041 --> 15:37.374
<i>that socialism stifles competition,</i>

15:37.753 --> 15:40.521
<i>impeding technological progess.</i>

15:40.802 --> 15:45.382
May I jump in an remark,

15:45.998 --> 15:51.704
that one of the largest
cooperative projects

15:51.726 --> 15:54.670
and planned economies

15:54.763 --> 15:58.370
was ironically,

15:59.153 --> 16:02.174
the Apollo project

16:02.951 --> 16:07.911
to put the middle class American
on the moon.

16:09.089 --> 16:11.388
So, let's have a ...

16:12.342 --> 16:14.114
...and technology...

16:20.017 --> 16:21.863
I'm at six G.

16:22.026 --> 16:23.693
Excuse me for a moment...

16:31.740 --> 16:33.847
<i>This is Hans Platzgaumer.</i>

16:34.327 --> 16:37.348
<i>He enjoys craft beer
and gory movies...</i>

16:37.501 --> 16:39.168
<i>in the Italian tradition.</i>

16:40.675 --> 16:42.886
<i>And, he's a passionate gamer.</i>

16:43.840 --> 16:45.268
Jesus!

16:49.957 --> 16:53.290
You're going to need some lube
and a tow truck

16:53.745 --> 16:56.025
to pull my boot out of your ass!

16:57.809 --> 17:00.452
<i>Do you have a minute
to talk about something important?</i>

17:00.504 --> 17:01.504
Huh?

17:01.622 --> 17:03.145
Where's this voice coming from?

17:03.367 --> 17:05.767
<i>I am your cerebral cortex.</i>

17:05.972 --> 17:07.175
<i>Listen!</i>

17:07.219 --> 17:08.219
That's weird.

17:08.810 --> 17:12.718
<i>Through the dark and not so dark
millennia of human history,</i>

17:12.976 --> 17:16.512
<i>we've organized ourselves into
adversarial cliques,</i>

17:16.667 --> 17:19.127
<i>communities and nations.</i>

17:19.363 --> 17:24.156
<i>World events were like
deadly ping pong balls hurtling towards us.</i>

17:24.281 --> 17:27.815
<i>And these groups were the paddles,
whose goal it was</i>

17:27.961 --> 17:30.961
<i>to knock the ball
into someone else's court.</i>

17:31.842 --> 17:33.903
What a crazy-ass metaphor!

17:34.189 --> 17:35.574
<i>Add military might,</i>

17:35.632 --> 17:37.672
<i>as the means to hold in place</i>

17:37.837 --> 17:40.237
<i>the lopsided system of distribution</i>

17:40.549 --> 17:44.530
<i>in which workers create
more and more economic value</i>

17:44.601 --> 17:48.583
<i>for wages... that never quite
grow at the same rate.</i>

17:49.068 --> 17:50.377
<i>And, lo,</i>

17:50.412 --> 17:52.522
<i>competion became the fabric</i>

17:52.627 --> 17:54.961
<i>in which everyday life was dressed.</i>

17:55.560 --> 17:57.321
<i>The technology necessary</i>

17:57.396 --> 17:59.095
<i>for global cooperation</i>

17:59.300 --> 18:00.841
<i>did not exist.</i>

18:01.156 --> 18:03.506
<i>Comptetition was thus established</i>

18:03.634 --> 18:06.868
<i>as the default way of
interacting with the world.</i>

18:07.342 --> 18:11.771
<i>In its genteel form,
competition meant nobody got killed.</i>

18:12.084 --> 18:14.210
<i>Gladiators turned to soccer....</i>

18:14.391 --> 18:16.604
<i>or turned to table tennis.</i>

